 mid-twentieth-century documentary photography and proceeding to early twenty-first-century drama, this project examines performances of blackness’s deadpan aesthetic within and beyond black embodiments, including Young Jean Lee’s The Shipment and Branden Jacobs-Jenkins’s Neighbors, as well as Buster Keaton’s signature character and Steve McQueen’s restitution of the former’s legacy within the continuum of Black cultural production. Through this varied archive, Post reveals how deadpan aesthetics function in and between opacity and fugitivity, minimalism and saturation, excess and insensibility.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAesthetics2DLC. 0aAfrican American arts. 0aAfrican Americans in art. 0aAfrican Americans in literature. 0aAmerican literaturexAfrican American authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aBlack peoplexRace identity2DLC. 0aBody language2DLC. 0aFacexPsychological aspects. 0aFacial expression in art. 0aFacial expression in literature. 0aFacial expression2DLC. 0aFacial expressionxPsychological aspects. 7aART / Performance.2bisacsh  aAesthetics.  aAnthropomorphism.  aAwayness.  aBlackness.  aDeadpan.  aEmpiricism.  aExcess.  aFaçade.  aFugitivity.  aIndestructability.  aInexpression.  aInsentience.  aKeaton.  aLooming.  aMcQueen.  aMinimalism.  aMinstrel.  aModernity.  aMonochrome.  aObjecthood.  aObscurity.  aOpacity.  aPortraiture.  aRespectability.  aRiddle.  aSheerness.  aSpecimen.  aStereotype.  aSubjectivity.  aTheatrical.  aThreat.  aTransparency.  aaffect.  agesture.  aperformance.  aresistance.  avisuality.40uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9781479811243.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781479811243423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781479811243/original  aEBA_EM